metadata.name: Ephemeral Fountain v1.0 #51
metadata.description:
This project originated with me thinking about how to do very realistic glass spheres that can be manipulated and moved within the THREE.js environment. Mixing that with several hundred ephemeral non-glass objects which are moving in a fountain-like flow, adding reflection and refraction to the glass, and combining it all in a physical existence which I playfully only impose on the non-glass objects nearby... in this world, glass can move through glass, with interesting effects similar to diamonds firing when light hits them at just the right angle! 

Extremely rare to get 8 glass spheres... By the randomness imposed, 30% will have one sphere, 30% two, 20% three, 10% four, 5% five, 3% six, 1% seven and 1% eight. Happy hunting!

metadata.name: simpel #84
metadata.description:
"simpel" german for basic/simple is my first collection that features generative art. The projects focus is layed on basic shapes and colors without using shaders or animations. 
In this world where everyone tries to be better and different, looking back at the "simpel" things might be a good choice.

“Simplicity is the ultimate sophistication.” — Leonardo da Vinci
“Less is more.” — Mies van der Rohe

Made in p5js
Created January 2023
By @nicolus_999 - nicolus_genArt

metadata.name: Gerhard #399
metadata.description:
Gerhard is a collaboration of Richard Nadler and Leander Herzog on fxhash. A generative animation based on multiple layers of color and data, mixed, moved and painted over in realtime. Some fragments stick to the canvas while others get discarded to leave the existing layers visible, allowing a complex surface to emerge and build up over time. 
Richard Nadler created the textures to control composition and color. Leander Herzog created the code for the interplay between the layers, motion and interactions. Both artists use different tools and are not aware of the details of each others process, meeting through the interface of pixels. This collaboration is enabled by twitter and fxhash, as the generative art community continues to explore abstraction in summer 2022 – while extreme temperatures, wildfires, ongoing conflicts and volatile markets continue to escalate. 

- Click to start a new layer of motion and color. 
- Doubleclick to enter fullscreen mode. 
- Press “s” to save the current canvas. 
- Append ?dpr=4 to the url to increase the resolution.

https://leanderherzog.ch/2022/gerhard/

metadata.name: Cockcoins #1
metadata.description:
Welcome to the cocktoid currency, Cockcoins! These coins can be redeemed for custom Dickgenerate art. The Dickgenerate art piece will most likely be in the style of Trebonius, which is a piece that has not debuted yet. Additional rules apply, see below:

- You must submit coins with a total of at least 100
-- every coin is worth it's face value times the multiplier from its shape
--- circle = 1
--- square = 2
--- hexagon = 3
-- one set of coins can only be redeemed for one drawing
- You can only request colors that are present within the Cockcoins you submitted
-- submitting one black coin lets you choose any colors (up to 5)
--- you can only fit so many colors into a Dickgenerative art, I will try to be accommodating

Further more, depending on the randomness of the mints I may drop the price of requesting a custom piece. The expected value of the mints is so that 100 is a fair price, but I will adjust accordingly if requests are low.

metadata.name: Neo-Retro Building #58
metadata.description:
"Depicting architectural"

The idea of depicting architectural designs for buildings in the future dates back to the 19th century with the rise of industrialization and advancements in technology. Architects and artists began to imagine what cities and buildings of the future might look like, often featuring towering skyscrapers, flying cars, and sleek, modern designs.

One early example is the 1889 World's Fair in Paris, which featured a "City of the Future" exhibit that showcased a vision of a highly-developed, technologically advanced metropolis. In the early 20th century, architects such as Le Corbusier proposed designs for "machine for living" buildings that were meant to be efficient and functional, with an emphasis on clean lines and minimal ornamentation.

In the decades that followed, architects and designers continued to create images of future buildings and cities, with an increasing focus on sustainability and eco-friendliness. This can be seen in concepts like the "smart city," which envisions cities that are highly connected and responsive to the needs of citizens, and designs for buildings that incorporate renewable energy sources and green spaces.

metadata.name: (Dis)ordered loom #61
metadata.description:
"Disordered loom" continues my exploration on texture, points, lines and noise, now in a grid within a grid. With the 'r' key you can toggle between an ordered and disordered loom, the disorder is created by an assigned subset of 4 sets of rotations. With the 't' key you can toggle translation, an additional movement is added/subtracted. With the 'e' key you can toggle more entropy.

You can further self-curate your token by clicking the canvas, colours change with each click, with the 'c' key you can remove a colour, you can press 'c' until two colours remain, with the 'v' key you can reset colours.

With the 'm' key you can mix all possible textures, press 'm' again to switch to your assigned texture. 

With the '+'/'-' keys you can alter the grain, "Disordered loom" implements the p5.grain addon.

Press 'e' to toggle entropy
Press 'r' to toggle between ordered/disordered loom
Press 't' to toggle translation
Press 'm' for mixed textures mode
Press 'c' to remove a color
Press 'v' to reset colors
Press '+'/'-' to alter the grain
Press 's' to save a png image
Press 'j' to save a jpg image
Press 'x' to save a higher resolution png

Ancient generative patterns.

Press 's' or double click/tap to save a PNG
To save 2x, 4x, or 8x versions, press the '2', '3', '4' keys respectively.

Made with thi.ng.

metadata.name: I'm in the world, but I'm not of it #125
metadata.description:
This piece resembles an abstract physical painting, but does not hide the hard edges and polygons that show its digital origins.

The title of this piece comes from "I'm in the world" by Moondog.

Libraries: p5.js
